+
+# Third-Party Structural Review SOP
+
+## Purpose
+
+Before implementation, send designs and significant code changes to a removed third party for structural conformance review. The third party checks: "does this follow our rules?" — not "is this good software?"
+
+## When to Trigger
+
+| Trigger | Required? |
+|---|---|
+| New architecture design document | Yes |
+| New ADR with `[DECISION REQUIRED]` | Yes |
+| New process template for governance bus | Yes |
+| Significant code change (new subsystem, new endpoint pattern, new data model) | Yes |
+| Bug fix, typo fix, dependency bump | No |
+| Reversible Act-mode changes within existing patterns | No |
+
+Rule of thumb: if the change introduces a new **shape** (new pattern, new integration, new authority file), it gets structural review. If it fills in an existing shape, it does not.
+
+## Procedure
+
+### 1. Prepare the Context Pack
+
+Assemble these files for the reviewer:
+
+```
+STRUCTURAL_CONTEXT_PACK/
+├── 00_authority/PRINCIPLES.md
+├── 00_authority/OPINION_CONFIDENCE.md
+├── 00_authority/SIGNATURES.md
+├── 02_build/routing/epistemic_status.py
+├── 00_authority/OPS_AUDIT_FRAMEWORK.md
+└── <the artifact being reviewed>
+```
+
+Do NOT include: session history, Linear tickets, agent conversations, Brain context, operational state. The reviewer judges the artifact against the structure, not the situation.
+
+### 2. Send to Reviewer
+
+Current reviewer: **Perplexity** (indicator node, removed, read-only, stateless).
+
+Prompt template:
+
+> Review this [design/code/ADR] against the Amplified Partners structural context provided. Check for:
+>
+> 1. Five Rods conformance (radical honesty, transparency, attribution, win-win, idea meritocracy)
+> 2. Epistemic discipline (tiers correctly assigned, no status laundering)
+> 3. Two-stage filtering (input rejection + output validation present)
+> 4. Missing pieces (what does the structure require that this doesn't include?)
+> 5. Risk assessment (what could go wrong, stated with radical honesty)
+>
+> Output your opinion as: what's good, what's missing, what risks exist, what you'd change. Assign confidence to each finding. You are an indicator node — you record your opinion, you do not decide.
+
+### 3. Record the Review
+
+The review opinion becomes a Vellum entry:
+
+```json
+{
+  "entry_type": "structural_review",
+  "author": "perplexity",
+  "epistemic_tier": "STRUCTURED",
+  "content": "<review summary>",
+  "metadata": {
+    "artifact_reviewed": "<path or title>",
+    "reviewer_role": "indicator_node",
+    "findings_count": 4,
+    "risks_count": 3
+  }
+}
+```
+
+When the governance bus is live, this entry joins the process chain. Until then, record the review as a comment on the PR or as a file in `03_shadow/reviews/`.
+
+### 4. Incorporate or Reject
+
+The baton holder reads the review and decides:
+
+- **Incorporate**: update the design with the finding. Attribute the finding to the reviewer.
+- **Reject**: proceed without the change. Record the rejection with reasoning and confidence.
+- **Defer**: acknowledge the finding, file it for a later phase. Attribute and link.
+
+All three actions are valid. The review is an indicator, not a gate.
+
+### 5. Proceed to Implementation
+
+After the baton holder has processed the review, implementation begins. The structural review entry becomes part of the governance trail — visible in the process view, linked to the PR lifecycle.
+
+## What the Reviewer IS and IS NOT
+
+| IS | IS NOT |
+|---|---|
+| An indicator node | A decision-maker |
+| Removed from operations | Part of the baton rotation |
+| Pattern recognition | Statistical validation |
+| Honest opinion with attribution | Authoritative judgment |
+| STRUCTURED epistemic tier | MEASURED or PROVEN |
+| A net that catches design flaws | A person to blame when flaws slip through |
+
+## Two-Stage Filtering (Where This Fits)
+
+```
+Input Filters (Rejection on the way in)
+    ↓
+Clean Data in the System
+    ↓
+Design / Architecture (agent work)
+    ↓
+Third-Party Structural Review  ← THIS GATE
+    ↓
+Implementation
+    ↓
+Output Filters (Validation on the way out)
+    ↓
+Operational Decision
+```
+
+The structural review is the filter between design and implementation. Input filters protect the system from bad data. Output filters protect the world from bad decisions. The structural review protects the codebase from designs that don't conform to the structure.
+
+---
+
+Signed-by: Devon | 2026-05-24 | devin-bfbc7fe01e7c43dda8cbbb7f9d4a73ec
